<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-clt">
    <title>The central limit theorem</title>
    <p>
        The sampling distribution of the mean depends on the sample size. As the sample size increases, 
        the sample mean becomes more consistent from one sample to another. Consequently, 
        the sampling distribution becomes increasingly concentrated around the population mean, 
        indicating that larger samples generally provide more precise estimates of the population parameter.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-IQsampa">
        <caption>
            An illustration of the how sampling distribution of the mean depends on sample size. I generated
            10,000 samples of IQ data, and calculated the mean IQ observed within each of
            these data sets. The histogram shows the distribution of these means (i.e., the sampling
            distribution of the mean). The individual IQ score was drawn from a normal distribution with mean 100
            and standard deviation 15, which is shown as the solid black line). In this plot, each data set contained
            only a single observation, so the mean of each sample is just one person's IQ score. As a consequence,
            the sampling distribution of the mean is of course identical to the population distribution of IQ scores.
            <xref ref="fig-IQsampb"/> illustrates when the sample size at 2, and <xref ref="fig-IQsampc"/> for a sample size of 10.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/IQsampa.png"/>
    </figure>
    <figure xml:id="fig-IQsampb">
        <caption>
            An illustration of the how sampling distribution of the mean depends on sample size. I generated
            10,000 samples of IQ data, and calculated the mean IQ observed within each of
            these data sets. The histogram shows the distribution of these means (i.e., the sampling
            distribution of the mean). The individual IQ score was drawn from a normal distribution with mean 100
            and standard deviation 15, which is shown as the solid black line). In this plot, each data set contained
            two observations. The mean of any one sample tends to be closer to the
            population mean than a one person's IQ score, and so the histogram (i.e., the sampling distribution)
            is a bit narrower than the population distribution.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/IQsampb.png"/>
    </figure>
    <figure xml:id="fig-IQsampc">
        <caption>
            An illustration of the how sampling distribution of the mean depends on sample size. I generated
            10,000 samples of IQ data, and calculated the mean IQ observed within each of
            these data sets. The histogram shows the distribution of these means (i.e., the sampling
            distribution of the mean). The individual IQ score was drawn from a normal distribution with mean 100
            and standard deviation 15, which is shown as the solid black line. In this plot, each data set contained
            ten observations. The distribution of sample means tend to be fairly tightly clustered around the true
            population mean.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/IQsampc.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
        Figures <xref ref="fig-IQsampa"/>, <xref ref="fig-IQsampb"/>, and <xref ref="fig-IQsampc"/> illustrate this effect for 
        increasing sample sizes. As the sample size increases, the spread of the sampling distribution decreases. 
        The standard deviation of the sampling distribution is known as the <em>standard error</em> (SE). 
        When referring specifically to the sample mean, it is called the <em>standard error of the mean</em> (SEM). 
        A smaller standard error indicates that sample means are more tightly clustered around the population mean and therefore 
        provide more precise estimates.
    </p>

    <p>
        So far, the examples have assumed that the population follows a normal distribution. 
        An important question is whether these results still hold when the population distribution is not normal. 
        The answer is provided by one of the most important results in statistics: the <em>Central Limit Theorem</em>.
    </p>

    <p>
        The Central Limit Theorem states that, regardless of the shape of the population distribution, 
        the sampling distribution of the sample mean becomes approximately normal as the sample size increases, 
        provided that the observations are independent and the sample size is sufficiently large. 
        Figures <xref ref="fig-cltdemo"/>, <xref ref="fig-cltdemoa"/>, <xref ref="fig-cltdemob"/>, 
        and <xref ref="fig-cltdemoc"/> illustrate this principle. Although the original population distribution is clearly 
        non-normal, the sampling distribution of the mean becomes increasingly bell-shaped as the sample size grows.
    </p>
    
    <figure xml:id="fig-cltdemo">
        <caption>
            A demonstration of the central limit theorem. Here, we have a non-normal population
            distribution; and <xref ref = "fig-cltdemoa"/>-<xref ref = "fig-cltdemoc"/> show the sampling
            distribution of the mean for samples of size 2,4 and 8, for data drawn from the
            distribution in panel a. As you can see, even though the original population
            distribution is non-normal, the sampling distribution of the mean becomes pretty
            close to normal by the time you have a sample of even 4 observations.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/cltdemo.png"/>
    </figure>
    <figure xml:id="fig-cltdemoa">
        <caption>
            A demonstration of the central limit theorem.
            Here we see the sampling distribution of the mean for samples of size 2 for data drawn from the
            distribution in <xref ref = "fig-cltdemo"/>. As you can see, even though the original population
            distribution is non-normal, the sampling distribution of the mean becomes pretty
            close to normal as the sample size increases.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/cltdemoa.png"/>
    </figure>
    <figure xml:id="fig-cltdemob">
        <caption>
            A demonstration of the central limit theorem.
            Here we see the sampling distribution of the mean for samples of size 4 for data drawn from the
            distribution in <xref ref = "fig-cltdemo"/>. As you can see, even though the original population
            distribution is non-normal, the sampling distribution of the mean becomes pretty
            close to normal as the sample size increases.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/cltdemob.png"/>
    </figure>
    <figure xml:id="fig-cltdemoc">
        <caption>
            A demonstration of the central limit theorem.
            Here we see the sampling distribution of the mean for samples of size 8 for data drawn from the
            distribution in <xref ref = "fig-cltdemo"/>. As you can see, even though the original population
            distribution is non-normal, the sampling distribution of the mean becomes pretty
            close to normal as the sample size increases.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/cltdemoc.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
        The Central Limit Theorem establishes three important properties of the sampling distribution of the mean:
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The mean of the sampling distribution is equal to the population mean (<m>\mu</m>).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The standard deviation of the sampling distribution, known as the standard error, 
                    decreases as the sample size increases.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    For sufficiently large samples, the sampling distribution of the mean is approximately normal, 
                    regardless of the shape of the population distribution.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
        More formally, if a population has mean <m>\mu</m> and standard deviation <m>\sigma</m>, 
        then the sampling distribution of the sample mean also has mean <m>\mu</m>, 
        and the standard error of the mean is given by
        <md>
            \mbox{SEM}=\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{N}}
        </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        This relationship shows that the standard error decreases as the sample size increases because the population standard 
        deviation is divided by the square root of the sample size.
    </p>
    <p>
        The Central Limit Theorem is one of the cornerstones of statistical inference. 
        It explains why larger samples generally produce more reliable estimates of population parameters and why the normal 
        distribution appears so frequently in statistical methods. The theorem also provides the theoretical foundation for confidence intervals, 
        hypothesis tests, and many other inferential procedures introduced later in this book.
    </p>
</subsection>    
